04221nam a22006135i 9780674054608DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222009mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740546087 a10.4159/97806740546082doi  a(DE-B1597)584771  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aB2798b.S515 2009 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a1932221 aShell, Susan Meld, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKant and the Limits of Autonomy /cSusan Meld Shell. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (444 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Taking Autonomy Seriously -- tI GETTING THERE -- t1 “Carazan’s Dream”: Kant’s Early Theory of Freedom -- t2 Kant’s Archimedean Moment: Remarks in “Observations Concerning the Feeling of the Beautiful and the Sublime” -- t3 Rousseau, Count Verri, and the “True Economy of Human Nature”: Lectures on Anthropology, 1772–1781 -- t4 The “Paradox” of Autonomy -- tII COMPLICATIONS ON ARRIVAL -- tIntroduction to Part II: Late Kant, 1789–1798 -- t5 Moral Hesitation in Religion within the Boundaries of Bare Reason -- t6 Kant’s “True Politics”: Völkerrecht in Toward Perpetual Peace and The Metaphysics of Morals -- t7 Kant as Educator: The Conflict of the Faculties, Part One -- t8 Archimedes Revisited: Honor and History in The Conflict of the Faculties, Part Two -- t9 Kant’s Jewish Problem -- tConcluding Remarks: The Limits of Autonomy -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAutonomy for Kant is not just a synonym for the capacity to choose, whether simple or deliberative. It is what the word literally implies: the imposition of a law on one’s own authority and out of one’s own rational resources. In Kant and the Limits of Autonomy, Shell explores the limits of Kantian autonomy—both the force of its claims and the complications to which they give rise. Through a careful examination of major and minor works, Shell argues for the importance of attending to the difficulty inherent in autonomy and to the related resistance that in Kant’s view autonomy necessarily provokes in us. Such attention yields new access to Kant’s famous, and famously puzzling, Groundlaying of the Metaphysics of Morals. It also provides for a richer and more unified account of Kant’s later political and moral works; and it highlights the pertinence of some significant but neglected early writings, including the recently published Lectures on Anthropology. Kant and the Limits of Autonomy is both a rigorous, philosophically and historically informed study of Kantian autonomy and an extended meditation on the foundation and limits of modern liberalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAutonomy (Philosophy). 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674054608zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674054608423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674054608/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK